in this case, how do I make sure CriticalTimeStep works with TET?
Also from this equation provided here: https://mooseframework.inl.gov/modules/solid_mechanics/CriticalTimeStepMath.html

how does it come down to this in
https://github.com/idaholab/moose/blob/next/modules/solid_mechanics/src/postprocessors/CriticalTimeStep.C
void
CriticalTimeStep::execute()
{
  const Real dens = _material_density[0];
  const Real dens_scaling = _density_scaling ? (*_density_scaling)[0] : 0.0;

  // In the above line, density is inferred only at the first quadrature point
  // of each element. Since critical time step is computed across all elements and
  // a minimum is then taken, this is okay.
  _critical_time = std::min(_factor * _current_elem->hmin() * std::sqrt(dens + dens_scaling) /
                                (_effective_stiffness[0]),
                            _critical_time);
}

for your first comment, I think the error is that you are missing the parameter in the validParams
you should have
 InputParameters params = Function::validParams();
 params.addClassDescription("Provide the sink value");
  params.addParam<MaterialPropertyName>("value_mat", <a default if it makes sense, if not then none>, "description");
 return params;

params.addParam<MaterialPropertyName>("value_mat", <a default if it makes sense, if not then none>, "description");

Replace <a default if it makes sense, if not then none> with a a default
If you dont understand what I mean, replace with this, which gives a 0 default
params.addParam<MaterialPropertyName>("value_mat", "0",  "description");

